The Sultan of Sokoto, Muhammadu Sa’ad Abubakar, yesterday declared that Ramadan begins today, admonishing Muslims to rededicate themselves to the teachings of Islam during the period His declaration followed the sighting of the new crescent in various parts of the country. The Sultan urged Muslims to commence the month-long fasting accordingly. He further enjoined them to pray fervently for the blessings of Allah to the nation’s leaders and for the sustenance of peace in the country. The monarch urged Muslim faithful to live peacefully with one another irrespective of religious and tribal differences. The Secretary-General, Nigerian Supreme Council for Islamic Affairs, Prof. Is-haq Oloyede, told Daily Trust on the telephone that the crescent was sighted in Sokoto, Kebbi and Yobe states. Meanwhile, the Sokoto State government is to expend   N380 million on this year’s Ramadan feeding programme. Governor Aminu Tambuwal, who disclosed this yesterday in Sokoto, said   an increase  was approved from the previous N300 million to N380 million for the programme to create additional feeding centres in the state. Tambuwal, represented  by his deputy, Manir Mohammed Dan-Iya,  spoke at the flag-off of the distribution of the 2018 zakkat, Sokoto State 2019 Ramadan package Qatar charity for the poor, at the auditorium of Sultan Muhammad Maccido institute for Quran and General Studies, Sokoto. Sultan urges Muslims to pray for Buhari, others as Ramadan begins Ramadan begins today Controversy trails commencement of Ramadan in Ilorin Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin